1
00:01:09,320 --> 00:01:11,189
[ Man ] All right, people, let's go!
Let's go!

2
00:01:11,322 --> 00:01:13,191
[ Man #2 ] Let's go, everybody!
We need your help here!

3
00:01:13,324 --> 00:01:15,193
Come up here! Get in here, get in here!
She's close!

4
00:01:15,326 --> 00:01:17,195
Vitals are down to nothing.

5
00:01:17,328 --> 00:01:19,197
Here you go. Come on.
Let me get in here. You got her?

6
00:01:19,330 --> 00:01:21,299
- We're clear. We're clear.
- I got it.

7
00:01:21,432 --> 00:01:24,636
- All right, lift her up on three.
One, two, three. Up.
- Who's hanging blood?

8
00:01:24,769 --> 00:01:26,638
- Can you hear me? Can you hear me?
- Get in there.
Get her prepped. Let's move!

9
00:01:26,771 --> 00:01:28,640
Let's go! Let's go!
We need some room!

10
00:01:28,773 --> 00:01:30,642
Spread it out, spread it out!
Let's make a hole! Come on!

11
00:01:30,775 --> 00:01:32,677
- Get a sterile pack!
- Right down the hallway, please!

12
00:01:32,811 --> 00:01:35,213
- Let's go! In here!
- [ Thunder Claps ]

13
00:01:35,313 --> 00:01:39,150
[ Thunder Rumbling ]

14
00:01:39,250 --> 00:01:43,154
[ Thunder Claps ]

15
00:01:43,254 --> 00:01:46,491
[ Thunder Rumbling ]

16
00:01:46,591 --> 00:01:51,830
[ Rumbling Continues ]

17
00:02:05,043 --> 00:02:08,614
- [ Sighs ] Anna didn't make it, Greg.
- [ Sobs ]

18
00:02:08,714 --> 00:02:13,352
- We tried everything.
The trauma was just too much.
- [ Sniffles, Sighs ]

19
00:02:13,452 --> 00:02:16,455
[ Sighs ] The baby?

20
00:02:19,024 --> 00:02:24,096
The baby, I'm concerned,
might have some abnormalities.

21
00:02:24,196 --> 00:02:29,368
Outwardly, we can already tell
that the child has no pigmentation.

22
00:02:29,468 --> 00:02:33,772
It's called albinism.
It's strictly genetic.

23
00:02:33,872 --> 00:02:36,041
That's, that's--
Well, that's pale skin, right?

24
00:02:36,141 --> 00:02:41,180
And pale eyes that are
usually more light sensitive.

25
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:45,284
- I want to see him.
- Greg, you have to remember
that an unborn child...

26
00:02:45,384 --> 00:02:48,287
experiences everything
that the mother experiences.

27
00:02:48,387 --> 00:02:52,658
You take me to him.
You show me.

28
00:02:52,758 --> 00:02:57,630
[ Baby Crying ]

29
00:02:57,730 --> 00:03:01,067
[ Crying Continues ]

30
00:03:01,167 --> 00:03:06,072
[ Monitor Beeping,
Crying Continues ]

31
00:03:08,174 --> 00:03:12,311
[ Continues Crying ]

32
00:03:12,412 --> 00:03:17,417
[ Crying Continues,
Monitor Beeping ]

33
00:03:17,517 --> 00:03:21,487
[ Continues Crying ]

34
00:03:21,588 --> 00:03:25,925
[ Crying Continues ]

35
00:03:26,025 --> 00:03:30,930
[ Baby Gasping ]

36
00:03:31,030 --> 00:03:34,434
[ Cooing ]

37
00:03:37,871 --> 00:03:40,774
[ Whimpering ]

38
00:03:40,874 --> 00:03:45,946
[ Crying ]

39
00:03:50,550 --> 00:03:55,122
[ Screaming ]

40
00:03:55,222 --> 00:03:58,625
[ Doctor ] We'll do everything we can
for him, Greg. You know that.

41
00:03:58,725 --> 00:04:01,728
- [ Monitor Beeping ]
- [ Greg ] What are you doing to him?

42
00:04:01,828 --> 00:04:03,730
[ Doctor ]
We're measuring his brain waves.

43
00:04:03,830 --> 00:04:08,869
[ Crying Continues ]

44
00:04:08,969 --> 00:04:12,606
- You don't have to do this now.
- [ Monitor Beeping ]

45
00:04:12,706 --> 00:04:17,411
[ Crying Continues ]

46
00:04:17,511 --> 00:04:20,547
[ Beeping, Crying Continue ]

47
00:04:24,118 --> 00:04:26,053
[ Crying ]
That's not my son.

48
00:04:26,153 --> 00:04:32,026
- [ Baby Crying ]
- That's not my son.

49
00:04:32,126 --> 00:04:35,029
- [ Beeping ]
- [ Crying Continues ]

50
00:04:35,129 --> 00:04:38,366
- That's not my son.
- Come on, Greg, let's go.

51
00:04:38,466 --> 00:04:40,735
[ Crying ]

52
00:04:40,835 --> 00:04:44,071
- That's not my son.
- You don't need this.
For Christ's sake, let's go.

53
00:04:44,171 --> 00:04:49,143
[ Continues Crying ]

54
00:04:49,243 --> 00:04:51,512
[ Hand Hits Glass,
Continues Crying ]

55
00:04:51,612 --> 00:04:56,951
[ Beeping, Crying Continue ]

56
00:05:00,154 --> 00:05:04,058
[ Crying Echoes ]

57
00:05:06,160 --> 00:05:08,396
[ Birds Chirping ]

58
00:05:20,675 --> 00:05:23,078
- Not good, Sheriff.
- [ Car Door Closes ]

59
00:05:23,178 --> 00:05:27,749
[ Onlookers Chattering ]

60
00:05:27,849 --> 00:05:30,752
[ Chattering Continues ]

61
00:05:30,852 --> 00:05:32,754
- Jessie.
- [ Woman ] Doug.

62
00:05:32,854 --> 00:05:35,323
Thanks for making the drive.

63
00:05:35,423 --> 00:05:38,260
- Are we still in Wheaton County?
- Barely.

64
00:05:38,360 --> 00:05:41,630
- Did I ruin your Sunday?
- Well, I guess if somebody...

65
00:05:41,730 --> 00:05:43,932
was going to have to,
I'm glad it was you.

66
00:05:44,032 --> 00:05:45,934
[ Screen Door Squeaks Open ]

67
00:05:46,034 --> 00:05:49,604
Doug...
I can hear him again.

68
00:05:49,705 --> 00:05:52,941
- He's movin' around down there.
- Tell me you didn't try to talk to him.

69
00:05:53,041 --> 00:05:55,277
- You bet your ass I didn't.
- Good.

70
00:05:55,377 --> 00:05:57,446
Miss Caldwell.

71
00:06:00,983 --> 00:06:03,719
They said a boy, right?

72
00:06:03,819 --> 00:06:07,723
I'm guessing
that's what it is.

73
00:06:07,823 --> 00:06:09,892
The old man here
died last night.

74
00:06:09,992 --> 00:06:12,394
The neighbors found him this morning.

75
00:06:12,494 --> 00:06:16,165
- We figure the kid's his grandson.
- So where is he?

76
00:06:35,184 --> 00:06:37,286
He won't come up
from the cellar.

77
00:06:37,386 --> 00:06:41,591
He didn't report
his grandfather's death either.

78
00:06:44,527 --> 00:06:47,930
We already know
he died of natural causes.

79
00:06:48,030 --> 00:06:51,434
Doug, what am I doing here?

80
00:06:51,534 --> 00:06:53,703
The neighbors say
he may be retarded.

81
00:06:53,803 --> 00:06:55,938
One of them says deformed.

82
00:06:56,039 --> 00:06:57,941
You know, physically handicapped.

83
00:06:58,041 --> 00:07:00,209
I don't know.

84
00:07:00,310 --> 00:07:03,046
I couldn't for the life of me
think of who else to call.

85
00:07:03,146 --> 00:07:05,148
He's scared enough,
and I thought maybe you could...

86
00:07:05,248 --> 00:07:09,552
come down and talk him
out of there without us having
to go down and drag him out.

87
00:07:09,652 --> 00:07:15,392
Jessie... the neighbors talk about him
like he's some kind of a phantom.

88
00:07:15,492 --> 00:07:18,461
I haven't met one yet that
ever had a good look at him.

89
00:07:18,561 --> 00:07:21,364
What are you telling me, Doug?

90
00:07:21,464 --> 00:07:24,935
That the old folks
may have kept him down there...

91
00:07:25,068 --> 00:07:29,206
like some kind of a family secret.

92
00:07:29,306 --> 00:07:32,209
I don't know.

93
00:07:37,080 --> 00:07:38,982
Boy?

94
00:07:41,151 --> 00:07:44,588
I brought somebody to talk to you.
[ Grunting ]

95
00:07:56,333 --> 00:07:58,235
Hello?

96
00:08:01,939 --> 00:08:05,976
Hey, my name is Jessie.

97
00:08:06,110 --> 00:08:08,078
Are you okay down here?

98
00:08:15,519 --> 00:08:17,455
You think we could
turn a light on?

99
00:08:22,526 --> 00:08:26,063
Hey, if you're afraid,
you don't need to be. Not with me.

100
00:08:28,699 --> 00:08:31,602
[ Boy, Softly ]
I'm not afraid.

101
00:08:35,873 --> 00:08:38,075
What's your name?

102
00:08:38,209 --> 00:08:40,111
Powder.

103
00:08:42,046 --> 00:08:46,551
- Is that a name or a nickname?
- He was getting coffee and he fell.

104
00:08:46,684 --> 00:08:49,687
He jus--
He just fell over and died.

105
00:08:51,956 --> 00:08:53,958
I tried to help him.

106
00:08:54,092 --> 00:08:56,928
- I tried. He--
- [ Doug ] We know that.

107
00:08:57,028 --> 00:09:00,899
Son, I told you,
you're not in any trouble.

108
00:09:03,201 --> 00:09:07,672
- I'm sorry. I just want to see you.
- Why?

109
00:09:10,008 --> 00:09:14,279
Well, come on. Nobody's gonna hurt you.
It's all right.

110
00:09:14,412 --> 00:09:17,082
Give me your hand.
Come on.

111
00:09:51,216 --> 00:09:53,085
What's your real name, son?

112
00:09:58,057 --> 00:10:00,059
Jeremy Reed.

113
00:10:00,159 --> 00:10:02,361
You've been down here
all night, Jeremy.

114
00:10:04,697 --> 00:10:06,899
[ Jessie ] You must be starved.

115
00:10:06,999 --> 00:10:09,368
Could you get us something to eat?

116
00:10:11,103 --> 00:10:14,540
Anything. Sheriff?

117
00:10:17,009 --> 00:10:19,745
We'll be all right.

118
00:10:21,314 --> 00:10:23,316
Be right back.

119
00:10:28,921 --> 00:10:31,057
[ Footsteps Ascending Stairs ]

120
00:10:39,198 --> 00:10:42,335
Why didn't you tell anyone
when you knew he was dead?

121
00:10:42,435 --> 00:10:46,506
Why didn't you call the police?

122
00:10:46,606 --> 00:10:51,411
Grandpa said
there would be a day...

123
00:10:51,511 --> 00:10:53,446
when he would die...

124
00:10:53,546 --> 00:10:57,016
like Grandma died.

125
00:10:58,918 --> 00:11:03,023
And that people would come...

126
00:11:03,123 --> 00:11:06,026
and see me...

127
00:11:08,428 --> 00:11:10,964
and try and take me away.

128
00:11:14,134 --> 00:11:17,037
[ Radio Transmission,
Onlookers Chattering ]

129
00:11:18,839 --> 00:11:23,710
- Get back there.
Keep an ear, but don't go down.
- Yes, sir.

130
00:11:23,810 --> 00:11:25,979
Lucy, this is Barnum.

131
00:11:26,079 --> 00:11:28,181
[ Radio ] Go ahead, Sheriff. I'm here.

132
00:11:28,282 --> 00:11:32,719
We're still out at the Reeds'.
We got something out here
nobody's gonna believe.

133
00:11:59,547 --> 00:12:03,350
- You don't live down here?
- Mmm.

134
00:12:03,451 --> 00:12:05,920
I do most of the work
around the place... [ Sniffs ]

135
00:12:06,020 --> 00:12:08,489
at least until the sun
gets too high.

136
00:12:08,589 --> 00:12:11,359
Then the sunglasses
don't even help.

137
00:12:11,459 --> 00:12:13,394
Did you know they make
contact lenses now...

138
00:12:13,494 --> 00:12:16,597
that can protect your eyes
from the sun all the time?

139
00:12:16,697 --> 00:12:22,003
I read about them, but Grandpa
said they cost too much. [ Sniffs ]

140
00:12:27,675 --> 00:12:29,844
When's the last time
you were in school?

141
00:12:29,944 --> 00:12:33,047
I've never been to school.

142
00:12:33,147 --> 00:12:35,183
I read about it though.

143
00:12:36,551 --> 00:12:40,221
But you said you
read all these books?

144
00:12:48,196 --> 00:12:51,966
And... have you read this book?

145
00:12:56,638 --> 00:12:59,507
Well, I know college kids who
couldn't wade through this one.

146
00:13:01,343 --> 00:13:03,245
Pick a page.

147
00:13:06,448 --> 00:13:08,550
Two hundred and sixteen.

148
00:13:13,455 --> 00:13:16,024
"Where lies the final harbor,
whence we unmoor no more.

149
00:13:18,160 --> 00:13:23,265
"In what rapt ether sails the world
of which the weariest will never weary?

150
00:13:23,365 --> 00:13:26,001
"Where is the foundling's
father hidden?

151
00:13:26,101 --> 00:13:30,906
"Our souls are like those orphans whose
unwedded mothers die in bearing them.

152
00:13:33,475 --> 00:13:38,280
"And the secret of our paternity
lies in their grave,

153
00:13:38,380 --> 00:13:40,382
and we must there learn it."

154
00:13:45,454 --> 00:13:47,356
You know the whole book?

155
00:13:50,059 --> 00:13:51,961
I know 'em all.

156
00:14:07,276 --> 00:14:10,213
- Go clear 'em back.
- All right, everybody, let's move back.

157
00:14:10,313 --> 00:14:13,116
- And I mean back beyond the vehicles.
Let's go!
- [ Onlooker ] Okay.

158
00:14:50,086 --> 00:14:51,988
[ Hinges Squeak ]

159
00:14:58,528 --> 00:15:00,430
[ Birds Chirping ]

160
00:15:14,745 --> 00:15:17,681
It's all right.
You don't have to be afraid.

161
00:15:17,781 --> 00:15:20,684
You're afraid.

162
00:15:22,119 --> 00:15:25,456
You're afraid for me.

163
00:15:34,164 --> 00:15:37,067
[ Onlookers Chattering ]

164
00:15:45,042 --> 00:15:48,379
[ Sirens Blaring,
Radios Distorting, Static ]

165
00:15:48,479 --> 00:15:51,349
[ Sirens, Radios Continue ]

166
00:15:51,449 --> 00:15:53,351
[ Sirens, Radios Fade ]

167
00:15:56,487 --> 00:15:58,890
Why don't you get in here.

168
00:16:01,392 --> 00:16:03,294
I'll take that.

169
00:16:04,896 --> 00:16:06,798
[ Starts Engine ]

170
00:16:27,552 --> 00:16:30,922
[ Deputy ] You ever see so many goddamn
lightning rods on one house?

171
00:16:32,123 --> 00:16:35,193
I just got off the horn
with the coroner.

172
00:16:35,327 --> 00:16:38,763
He said that old boy died
of natural causes, but there
was evidence of fibrillation.

173
00:16:38,897 --> 00:16:41,032
His body was juiced
with electricity.

174
00:16:41,166 --> 00:16:43,668
That old man was laying
dead there all night.

175
00:16:43,802 --> 00:16:47,839
You think the paramedics showed up
this morning and tried paddles on him?

176
00:16:47,973 --> 00:16:50,575
Are you telling me the kid
electrocuted the old man?

177
00:16:50,709 --> 00:16:53,178
What do you think,
he's Dr. Frankenstein?

178
00:16:53,311 --> 00:16:56,848
I'm just sayin' that
that's more than an albino, Doug.

179
00:16:58,717 --> 00:17:01,453
That is spooky.

180
00:17:01,587 --> 00:17:05,490
I never thought we'd find a man
too white for you there, Harley.

181
00:17:18,671 --> 00:17:20,572
- Come on now, let me have it.
- [ Dog Barking ]

182
00:17:20,673 --> 00:17:22,574
[ Barking Continues ]

183
00:17:37,323 --> 00:17:40,593
[ Window Whirring ]

184
00:18:07,553 --> 00:18:10,456
[ Boys Chattering, Yelling ]

185
00:18:14,527 --> 00:18:16,429
[ Boys Continue Chattering ]

186
00:18:16,529 --> 00:18:20,500
- Okay, come on, let's go!
- Hut! Hut!

187
00:18:20,600 --> 00:18:23,036
- Down! Set!
- All right, set, you moron.

188
00:18:23,136 --> 00:18:25,038
Hut!

189
00:18:26,139 --> 00:18:28,041
[ Boy ] I got him! Come on!

190
00:18:28,141 --> 00:18:30,043
- [ Boys Chattering ]
- [ Jessie ] Don't let 'em fool you.

191
00:18:30,143 --> 00:18:32,512
They spend most their time
tryin' to look tough.

192
00:18:32,612 --> 00:18:35,315
You get to know 'em,
you find out they're...

193
00:18:35,415 --> 00:18:38,819
mostly scared and lonely
just like everybody else.

194
00:18:38,919 --> 00:18:41,655
[ Boys Continue Chattering ]

195
00:18:41,755 --> 00:18:45,692
- [ Boy #1 ] Come on!
- [ Boy #2 ] Fourth down!
It's on the line!

196
00:18:45,792 --> 00:18:49,229
- Hut! Go! Go!
- Geez, I'm open! I'm open!

197
00:18:49,329 --> 00:18:51,865
- Yeah!
- I got him! I got him! Got him! Get him!

198
00:18:51,965 --> 00:18:55,669
- [ Car Door Slams ]
- Come on, come on!
Get the ball! Come on, catch the--

199
00:18:55,769 --> 00:18:59,406
- [ Boys, Hushed ] Oh, man.
- Whoa.

200
00:19:02,176 --> 00:19:05,813
What the hell is that?

201
00:19:05,913 --> 00:19:09,817
You need to see him, Aaron,
to know what I'm saying.

202
00:19:09,917 --> 00:19:12,820
You need to see him sitting out
in the hall right now...

203
00:19:12,920 --> 00:19:16,824
'cause, I'm telling you,
I've never seen anything like him.

204
00:19:16,924 --> 00:19:18,993
That's exactly what I mean.

205
00:19:19,093 --> 00:19:22,163
Because of the way he's lived.

206
00:19:22,263 --> 00:19:25,633
Uh, he doesn't seem
to know what things are.

207
00:19:25,733 --> 00:19:28,502
I think things you and I
take for granted--

208
00:19:28,602 --> 00:19:31,839
common, everyday objects,
simple ideas--

209
00:19:31,939 --> 00:19:34,508
I just don't think
he's ever been exposed to them.

210
00:19:34,608 --> 00:19:39,347
I mean, he's about the most well-read
teenage kid you could ever meet.

211
00:19:39,447 --> 00:19:42,016
But in other ways...

212
00:19:42,116 --> 00:19:46,020
[ Whispers ] I think he's a lot
like a little child.

213
00:19:50,625 --> 00:19:54,362
[ Snickering, Murmuring ]

214
00:19:54,462 --> 00:19:57,365
[ Murmuring Continues ]

215
00:19:57,465 --> 00:19:59,701
[ Giggling ]

216
00:20:03,471 --> 00:20:07,375
[ Chattering ]

217
00:20:07,475 --> 00:20:11,346
[ Chattering Continues ]

218
00:20:11,446 --> 00:20:15,550
[ Chattering Continues ]

219
00:20:15,650 --> 00:20:19,387
[ Chuckling, Chattering ]

220
00:20:19,487 --> 00:20:22,557
[ Boys Laughing ]

221
00:20:25,260 --> 00:20:27,329
[ Continue Chattering ]

222
00:20:27,429 --> 00:20:29,331
[ Murmuring ]

223
00:20:48,951 --> 00:20:51,787
[ Chattering, Murmuring Stops ]

224
00:20:56,024 --> 00:20:58,026
Why you look like that?

225
00:20:58,127 --> 00:21:03,866
You look like some kind of vampire
from outer space or something.

226
00:21:03,966 --> 00:21:07,870
They kick you out
of cancer camp?

227
00:21:11,974 --> 00:21:14,543
You got some kind of disease?

228
00:21:17,146 --> 00:21:19,248
Don't look at me, man.

229
00:21:19,348 --> 00:21:22,385
Did you hear what I said?

230
00:21:22,485 --> 00:21:25,054
I don't like your eyes.

231
00:21:31,160 --> 00:21:33,896
[ Laughing, Murmuring ]

232
00:21:33,996 --> 00:21:36,199
What's a new guy gotta do
the first day he gets here?

233
00:21:36,299 --> 00:21:38,234
He's gotta do the due.

234
00:21:40,670 --> 00:21:45,575
New guy, first day, first meal.

235
00:21:48,177 --> 00:21:50,179
He's gotta wear his spoon.

236
00:21:50,280 --> 00:21:52,582
[ Laughing, Murmuring ]

237
00:21:52,682 --> 00:21:54,751
You ever wear your spoon?

238
00:21:57,187 --> 00:22:00,023
Well, you got two choices.

239
00:22:00,123 --> 00:22:02,025
You can either wear it
on the end of your nose--

240
00:22:02,125 --> 00:22:04,694
Why don't you show, Mitch.

241
00:22:10,900 --> 00:22:12,869
[ Exhales ]

242
00:22:15,972 --> 00:22:18,875
[ Laughing ]

243
00:22:18,975 --> 00:22:20,944
[ Snickers ]

244
00:22:21,044 --> 00:22:23,880
[ Laughing, Murmuring Continue ]

245
00:22:23,980 --> 00:22:25,882
Now, you can wear it
like that...

246
00:22:25,982 --> 00:22:30,053
or you can wear it the other way,
which is up your ass.

247
00:22:30,153 --> 00:22:33,357
- [ Murmuring, Laughing Continue ]
- You choose.

248
00:22:43,834 --> 00:22:46,537
[ Chuckles ]

249
00:23:00,351 --> 00:23:02,253
What are you doin'?

250
00:23:15,967 --> 00:23:18,035
Jesus!

251
00:23:18,135 --> 00:23:21,772
[ Boys Gasping, Shouting ]

252
00:23:21,872 --> 00:23:23,875
[ Boys Hush ]

253
00:23:51,503 --> 00:23:55,740
[ Tapping ]

254
00:23:59,778 --> 00:24:05,517
[ Tapping ]

255
00:24:09,688 --> 00:24:11,723
[ Clatters On Floor ]

256
00:24:33,712 --> 00:24:36,682
[ Silverware Crashes ]

257
00:25:18,558 --> 00:25:20,526
[ Closes Door ]

258
00:25:20,660 --> 00:25:25,965
[ Crickets Chirping, Owl Hooting ]

259
00:25:26,065 --> 00:25:30,036
[ Chirping, Hooting Continue ]

260
00:25:37,010 --> 00:25:39,012
Poppa.

261
00:26:03,503 --> 00:26:07,007
[ Car Door Opens, Closes ]

262
00:26:07,140 --> 00:26:10,177
[ Engine Starts, Revs ]

263
00:26:10,277 --> 00:26:13,213
[ Car Departing ]

264
00:26:26,126 --> 00:26:28,061
You see Steven?

265
00:26:45,479 --> 00:26:47,982
He stayed three hours.

266
00:26:49,316 --> 00:26:52,086
Did her more good
than them painkillers.

267
00:26:54,321 --> 00:26:57,558
She was hurtin' all day
'til he got here.

268
00:27:01,996 --> 00:27:03,998
[ Sighs ]

269
00:27:20,448 --> 00:27:23,351
He brought her that too.

270
00:27:33,461 --> 00:27:37,699
- What happened out
at the Reed farm today?
- I'm here, angel.

271
00:27:37,799 --> 00:27:43,204
Something about a retarded boy
they got up at the state home now.

272
00:27:43,305 --> 00:27:46,041
How the hell did you hear about that?

273
00:27:47,976 --> 00:27:51,246
I guess I don't have to tell you
what I think about that.

274
00:27:51,346 --> 00:27:54,316
- I'd love it if you didn't.
- The last thing we need up there...

275
00:27:54,416 --> 00:27:59,387
is another mental defective
along with all that other trash.

276
00:28:00,989 --> 00:28:04,159
[ Softly ] Here you go.

277
00:28:04,259 --> 00:28:06,495
[ Chews Ice ]

278
00:28:06,595 --> 00:28:10,732
I don't know what he is,
but retarded he's not.

279
00:28:17,473 --> 00:28:21,276
Well, aside from the absence
of any and all body hair,

280
00:28:21,376 --> 00:28:24,380
which is a condition
not too uniquely uncommon,

281
00:28:24,480 --> 00:28:26,849
bottom line,
he's a very healthy young man.

282
00:28:26,949 --> 00:28:29,885
In fact, with all that farm work,
I'd say you're in damn fine shape.

283
00:28:29,985 --> 00:28:32,788
And the optometrist said
his contact lenses'll be here...

284
00:28:32,888 --> 00:28:35,057
- the end of the week?
- [ Doctor ] They'll be callin' him
"Ol' Blue Eyes"...

285
00:28:35,157 --> 00:28:37,126
in time for the county fair.

286
00:28:37,226 --> 00:28:40,329
- You guys are comin', right?
- Uh, you'll see a few of us there.

287
00:28:40,429 --> 00:28:43,632
Hey, Doc, thanks for comin' out.

288
00:28:43,733 --> 00:28:47,803
It's my pleasure.
Good day, Mr. Jeremy Reed.

289
00:28:55,144 --> 00:28:59,315
Jeremy, listen, uh,
I want you to think about something.

290
00:28:59,415 --> 00:29:03,119
We attend school in town
at Wheaton High.

291
00:29:04,720 --> 00:29:09,492
You certainly wouldn't be at
an intellectual disadvantage there,

292
00:29:09,592 --> 00:29:12,128
and I know most
of the teachers so--

293
00:29:12,228 --> 00:29:15,265
Anyway, um, all I'm saying is,

294
00:29:15,365 --> 00:29:20,169
if you'd like to attend school
one day next week, I can arrange it.

295
00:29:24,007 --> 00:29:27,177
Will my contacts be ready by Monday?

296
00:29:31,314 --> 00:29:34,584
[ Students Chattering ]

297
00:29:34,684 --> 00:29:36,586
[ Continue Chattering ]

298
00:29:43,527 --> 00:29:45,929
[ Brakes Squeaking ]

299
00:29:46,029 --> 00:29:50,000
[ Chattering Continues ]

300
00:29:53,737 --> 00:29:55,639
[ Chattering Continues ]

301
00:29:57,174 --> 00:29:59,710
- Come on, let's go. Okay?
- Hey, there.

302
00:29:59,810 --> 00:30:01,712
- I left it in my locker.
- Hey, what is that?

303
00:30:01,812 --> 00:30:04,982
- I'll go get it.
- Hey, check it out.

304
00:30:07,584 --> 00:30:10,554
Hey, hey, guys.
Check that guy out.

305
00:30:10,654 --> 00:30:13,857
- Look, look.
- [ Girl Giggling ]

306
00:30:15,626 --> 00:30:18,529
[ Chattering Stops ]

307
00:30:23,934 --> 00:30:25,836
[ Chalk Squeaking ]

308
00:30:33,477 --> 00:30:36,280
[ Softly ] Molecules.

309
00:30:36,380 --> 00:30:41,319
When we speed up the course
of molecules, we get...

310
00:30:41,419 --> 00:30:43,888
[ Tapping Feet ]

311
00:30:43,988 --> 00:30:45,990
energy.

312
00:30:46,090 --> 00:30:50,228
And, um, since we
are all basically...

313
00:30:50,328 --> 00:30:54,398
just a mass of molecules,

314
00:30:54,499 --> 00:30:58,503
what does our brain send out
to all the other parts of the body?

315
00:30:58,603 --> 00:31:01,873
Lindsey?

316
00:31:01,973 --> 00:31:03,841
Um, impulses.

317
00:31:03,941 --> 00:31:07,545
Yeah.
Electric impulses.

318
00:31:10,381 --> 00:31:13,351
Jeremy, turn your head
and look at Lindsey.

319
00:31:14,886 --> 00:31:17,822
[ Students Snickering ]

320
00:31:19,090 --> 00:31:21,593
Yes. That's lovely.

321
00:31:21,693 --> 00:31:25,630
That's very good.
You've just relayed electricity.

322
00:31:25,730 --> 00:31:30,302
Your brain sent out
an electric impulse...

323
00:31:30,402 --> 00:31:32,904
down to your neck muscles...

324
00:31:33,004 --> 00:31:36,508
and, uh, what, what
turned your head,

325
00:31:36,608 --> 00:31:38,510
besides the obvious?

326
00:31:38,610 --> 00:31:43,048
What your, what your muscles
used to turn your head?

327
00:31:44,616 --> 00:31:47,185
[ Snapping Fingers ]
It's energy. Energy.

328
00:31:47,285 --> 00:31:51,657
Always relaying,
always transforming.

329
00:31:51,757 --> 00:31:54,893
And never ending.

330
00:31:54,993 --> 00:31:57,696
Now looky here.

331
00:31:57,796 --> 00:31:59,865
This is a, uh, a Jacob's ladder.

332
00:31:59,965 --> 00:32:02,034
It's a science fair toy,

333
00:32:02,134 --> 00:32:07,539
and it's, uh, built to show us
how electricity travels.

334
00:32:07,639 --> 00:32:09,541
Okay?

335
00:32:09,641 --> 00:32:12,845
Can we get the, uh, shutters?
Watch this.

336
00:32:12,945 --> 00:32:17,683
[ Teacher Sighs, Students Gasping ]

337
00:32:17,783 --> 00:32:19,952
Hey, cut it out.
Cut it out.

338
00:32:20,052 --> 00:32:25,024
[ Clicks Switch,
Electricity Buzzing ]

339
00:32:25,157 --> 00:32:29,862
[ Continues Buzzing ]

340
00:32:29,962 --> 00:32:33,966
- [ Students Chuckling ]
- [ Teacher ] Ooh, look at this.

341
00:32:34,100 --> 00:32:37,837
Blinding, isn't it? Now, who can tell me
why electricity travels?

342
00:32:37,937 --> 00:32:39,238
Uh, boredom?

343
00:32:39,338 --> 00:32:42,208
- [ Students Laughing ]
- Huh, he tickles me.

344
00:32:42,308 --> 00:32:47,513
No. No, potential.
Potential.

345
00:32:47,613 --> 00:32:50,383
One side of this thing is positive,
while the other side...

346
00:32:50,483 --> 00:32:52,552
has a strong negative pull.

347
00:32:52,685 --> 00:32:55,588
And, uh, that's all the potential
that electricity needs to travel.

348
00:32:55,688 --> 00:33:00,126
- [ Buzzing ]
- That's right.

349
00:33:00,260 --> 00:33:03,563
That's pretty good. Don't I bring you
good, entertaining things?

350
00:33:03,663 --> 00:33:07,333
But you get the idea that it
does-- You know, it-it travels
and just keeps going.

351
00:33:07,467 --> 00:33:09,369
Did you ever--
What's your experience with electricity?

352
00:33:09,469 --> 00:33:11,871
Did you ever, you know,
run your feet over a carpet
like that and touch somebody?

353
00:33:11,971 --> 00:33:14,641
- What happens?
- Static electricity?

354
00:33:14,774 --> 00:33:17,344
That's right, that's right. Now, where
does it go when y-you touch somebody?

355
00:33:17,477 --> 00:33:19,879
- [ Pen Spinning ]
- [ Teacher ] It just goes out.
So ener-- So, so electricity,

356
00:33:19,980 --> 00:33:24,684
like energy, uh,
just-just, um, uh, recycles.

357
00:33:24,818 --> 00:33:27,487
- [ Buzzing Louder ]
- It flows in a cycle that d-doesn't end.

358
00:33:27,621 --> 00:33:30,457
- It-It, uh--
- [ Buzzing Louder ]

359
00:33:30,557 --> 00:33:32,826
[ Buzzing Louder ]

360
00:33:37,731 --> 00:33:40,300
Are you all right?

361
00:33:43,470 --> 00:33:46,273
Mr. Ripley?

362
00:33:46,406 --> 00:33:49,810
[ Arcing Faster, Buzzing Louder ]

363
00:33:52,246 --> 00:33:54,248
Are you okay?

364
00:33:56,417 --> 00:33:59,687
[ Students Shouting ]

365
00:34:07,695 --> 00:34:10,664
[ Students Gasping ]

366
00:34:36,324 --> 00:34:40,061
[ Gasps ]

367
00:35:32,080 --> 00:35:36,184
The local news and
those Channel 5 people are outside.

368
00:35:36,285 --> 00:35:38,186
So is Jimmy Hobbs
from the newspaper.

369
00:35:38,287 --> 00:35:40,355
- Tell them to go home.
- Oh, come on, Doug.

370
00:35:40,455 --> 00:35:43,025
They ain't goin' anywhere 'til somebody
goes out there and talks to 'em.

371
00:35:43,125 --> 00:35:46,361
Tell them there's no fatalities, no sex
scandal. That will get rid of them fast.

372
00:35:46,462 --> 00:35:48,363
Goddamn it, Doug,
I sound like a moron...

373
00:35:48,464 --> 00:35:52,201
- if I say more than five words to
those people, and you know it.
- Well, if the shoe fits--

374
00:35:52,301 --> 00:35:54,203
[ P.A. System ] Dr. Tarentino,
you're wanted in Pediatrics.

375
00:35:54,303 --> 00:35:56,872
[ Doctor ] But I can't do it. I've got
no authorization to do anything.

376
00:35:56,972 --> 00:35:59,141
- I can't let you go anywhere--
- [ Doug ] Hi, Doc.

377
00:35:59,241 --> 00:36:02,978
Here we go, here we go.
Doug, Doug, tell Duane that it's
okay for me to see that kid.

378
00:36:03,078 --> 00:36:05,281
- Thank you.
- Donald, you're just the man
I wanted to see.

379
00:36:05,381 --> 00:36:08,384
I got 20 different kids
telling me 20 different stories.

380
00:36:08,484 --> 00:36:10,986
Right. Uh, if I hadn't seen it myself,
I'd say it was impossible.

381
00:36:11,087 --> 00:36:14,357
It was a model. For God sakes,
it picked him right out of his seat.

382
00:36:14,457 --> 00:36:17,193
- What did?
- Hold it! Ho-Hold it, Doug.

383
00:36:17,293 --> 00:36:19,996
The kid doesn't have a scratch on him.
Heart rate's a little irregular,

384
00:36:20,096 --> 00:36:22,999
but nothing to indicate the kind of
electrical shock you're talking about.

385
00:36:23,099 --> 00:36:26,903
Right, right! And he's got a hole,
uh, burned in his shirt...

386
00:36:27,003 --> 00:36:29,038
the size of a bowling ball.

387
00:36:29,138 --> 00:36:31,441
[ Ripley Sighs ]
Something's happened here.

388
00:36:31,541 --> 00:36:35,011
Something's happened here.
I'm telling you, with everything
we know about science,

389
00:36:35,111 --> 00:36:37,013
about the makeup of the human body,

390
00:36:37,113 --> 00:36:39,616
what happened in that classroom
is impossible!

391
00:36:39,716 --> 00:36:42,952
That kid attracted an arc
of electricity from 30 feet away!

392
00:36:43,052 --> 00:36:45,688
And not just from the Jacob's ladder.
I mean, after a second,
it was like it was...

393
00:36:45,788 --> 00:36:49,959
comin' at him out
of the whole... building.

394
00:36:50,059 --> 00:36:52,962
- You want to know why
there isn't a hair on him?
- [ Doug ] Why?

395
00:36:53,062 --> 00:36:57,200
Because he is electrolysis.
It can't grow on him.

396
00:36:59,502 --> 00:37:01,404
- [ Nurse ] Doc Roth?
- Yes?

397
00:37:01,504 --> 00:37:04,140
- Can I see you for a minute?
- Excuse me.

398
00:37:04,241 --> 00:37:07,510
- [ Nurse ] Excuse me.
- [ P.A. System ] Dr. McGrail
and Dr. Cain to C.C.U.

399
00:37:07,611 --> 00:37:09,813
- Drink that in.
- Dr. McGrail and Dr. Cain to C.C.U.

400
00:37:09,913 --> 00:37:11,948
[ Doug ] I will.

401
00:37:14,785 --> 00:37:16,853
Nobody saw him leave his room,

402
00:37:16,953 --> 00:37:20,323
- but his clothes are gone too.
- Find him.

403
00:37:20,424 --> 00:37:22,359
He can't have gotten far.

404
00:37:22,459 --> 00:37:24,428
[ P.A. System ]
Dr. Brodnick, call 2-9-2.

405
00:37:24,528 --> 00:37:27,030
- Dr. Brodnick, 2-9-2, please.
- Lucy, come in.

406
00:37:27,130 --> 00:37:29,066
[ Birds Chirping ]

407
00:37:42,312 --> 00:37:44,615
[ Dog Barking ]

408
00:37:44,715 --> 00:37:48,085
[ Barking Continues ]

409
00:37:48,185 --> 00:37:51,522
- [ Softly ] Hey.
- [ Growling, Barking ]

410
00:37:51,622 --> 00:37:54,291
- [ Barking, Growling Continue ]
- Zack! Zachary!

411
00:37:54,391 --> 00:37:56,627
Zack, come here.
Come here, boy.

412
00:37:56,727 --> 00:37:58,829
[ Barking ]

413
00:37:58,929 --> 00:38:02,333
- [ Growling ]
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. Watch out. He bites.

414
00:38:02,433 --> 00:38:04,635
[ Whimpering ]

415
00:38:04,735 --> 00:38:08,039
The family before us
made him pretty mean, so--

416
00:38:08,139 --> 00:38:11,842
Wow, I can't believe I'm looking at you.
Are you okay?

417
00:38:11,943 --> 00:38:16,447
- [ Zack Whimpering ]
- I didn't mean to scare anybody.

418
00:38:16,547 --> 00:38:20,685
- The whole thing was pretty
embarrassing really.
- Embarrassing?

419
00:38:20,785 --> 00:38:23,187
You're kidding, right?
[ Giggles ]

420
00:38:24,922 --> 00:38:28,393
My grandma used to say
I have an electric personality.

421
00:38:28,493 --> 00:38:31,195
[ Laughs ]
Well, that was some light show.

422
00:38:31,296 --> 00:38:33,831
I mean, people will
be talking about that...

423
00:38:33,932 --> 00:38:37,702
to their grandkids'
grandkids around here.

424
00:38:37,802 --> 00:38:40,472
I don't mean to stare,
but I had a bet with a friend...

425
00:38:40,572 --> 00:38:42,841
that you have blue-grey eyes.

426
00:38:42,941 --> 00:38:46,644
She says they're blue-green.

427
00:38:46,745 --> 00:38:49,381
Looks like she's right.

428
00:38:50,949 --> 00:38:54,052
Well, actually, you're...

429
00:38:55,520 --> 00:38:57,556
you're both wrong.

430
00:38:57,656 --> 00:39:00,292
Oh.

431
00:39:00,392 --> 00:39:03,161
Sorry.

432
00:39:03,261 --> 00:39:07,766
No, no, that's okay. Just kind of
took me by surprise, that's all.

433
00:39:07,866 --> 00:39:11,803
- [ Zack Panting ]
- [ Sighs ] Oh, well.

434
00:39:11,903 --> 00:39:14,072
- [ Raking ]
- [ Zack Barks ]

435
00:39:14,172 --> 00:39:17,976
- [ Continues Raking ]
- [ Lindsey ] You must feel
like you've got two heads...

436
00:39:18,076 --> 00:39:22,080
- the way everybody
looks at you around here, huh?
- [ Raking Continues ]

437
00:39:22,181 --> 00:39:27,152
Have you ever listened
to people from the inside?

438
00:39:27,252 --> 00:39:31,390
Listened so close,
you can hear their thoughts...

439
00:39:31,490 --> 00:39:34,460
and all their memories?

440
00:39:37,463 --> 00:39:42,535
Hear 'em think from places that
they don't even know they think from?

441
00:39:42,635 --> 00:39:44,537
What are you saying?
You can do that?

442
00:39:46,639 --> 00:39:49,308
Are you sure you're okay?
[ Nervous Laugh ]

443
00:39:54,246 --> 00:39:56,148
Do you know how to get
to the interstate?

444
00:39:56,248 --> 00:39:59,018
Yeah, it's um--

445
00:39:59,118 --> 00:40:01,454
If you follow the train tracks,
you'll see the Redmond water tower.

446
00:40:01,554 --> 00:40:04,924
Then, if you go across
the trestle, you'll see it.

447
00:40:05,024 --> 00:40:09,362
- But you're really okay?
- [ Softly ] I'm okay.

448
00:40:11,330 --> 00:40:13,666
You better hurry.

449
00:40:13,766 --> 00:40:17,770
They catch boys running away
from Central, I hear they get solitary.

450
00:40:17,904 --> 00:40:19,872
Hey!

451
00:40:22,241 --> 00:40:25,812
Stay away from
those electrical outlets, okay?

452
00:40:32,385 --> 00:40:34,287
[ Softly ] Bye.

453
00:40:41,461 --> 00:40:43,363
[ Birds Chirping ]

454
00:40:47,534 --> 00:40:49,436
[ Chirping Continues ]

455
00:41:27,341 --> 00:41:29,743
[ Engines Stop ]

456
00:41:52,266 --> 00:41:55,703
I didn't know better,
I'd say you were headed for the highway.

457
00:41:55,803 --> 00:41:58,039
Don't make me
come out there, boy.

458
00:42:02,877 --> 00:42:07,315
Now, you're about to make me
a whole lot meaner. Trust me, son,

459
00:42:07,448 --> 00:42:10,084
- you don't want to make me mad.
- Afraid.

460
00:42:12,120 --> 00:42:14,188
I don't make you mad,
I make you afraid.

461
00:42:14,322 --> 00:42:16,090
What was that?

462
00:42:16,224 --> 00:42:19,060
I said that
you're afraid of me.

463
00:42:19,194 --> 00:42:21,896
Duncan, get on back.

464
00:42:25,834 --> 00:42:27,802
I can handle this.

465
00:42:35,477 --> 00:42:38,613
I'm all right.

466
00:42:38,747 --> 00:42:41,283
- I can see that.
- [ Jeremy ] Then let me go home.

467
00:42:41,383 --> 00:42:43,685
I don't want to go back
to that hospital.

468
00:42:43,818 --> 00:42:47,689
We'll call the doc. If he says okay,
I'll take you back to Central.

469
00:42:47,789 --> 00:42:49,758
Central's not my home.

470
00:42:49,858 --> 00:42:54,129
[ Doug ] I'm trying to tell you
as nice as I know how.

471
00:42:54,229 --> 00:42:59,534
Now either you come with me
without a fuss or we're gonna
have ourselves a problem.

472
00:43:11,547 --> 00:43:14,717
You want me to cuff him?

473
00:43:21,090 --> 00:43:23,092
[ Engine Starts ]

474
00:43:24,393 --> 00:43:26,462
Lucy, this is One.
We got him.

475
00:43:26,562 --> 00:43:28,597
I'm coming back to the office.

476
00:43:28,697 --> 00:43:30,633
[ Transmission Distorts ]
...Doug.

477
00:43:30,733 --> 00:43:33,135
You got a problem
with hospitals in general?

478
00:43:33,235 --> 00:43:35,805
I don't like 'em.

479
00:43:35,905 --> 00:43:39,308
Well, you can put me
on that list.

